Think through the design of an API schema analysis tool that must give useful, actionable output to three fundamentally different audiences simultaneously: junior developers who are learning API design for the first time, senior engineers who want precision and no noise, and platform engineering teams who need organizational metrics and trend data.

The junior developer audience needs explanatory output: not just "this field is missing a format constraint" but "the field email has type string but no format: email constraint. Without this constraint, validation tools and mock generators will not know this is an email address. Adding format: email enables email-specific validation and realistic mock data generation." They need links to documentation, examples of correct patterns, and confidence that the tool is not flagging things that are actually fine.

The senior engineer audience wants the opposite: a terse, machine-parseable list of violations with precise rule identifiers, zero false positives, and the ability to suppress known-acceptable deviations with an inline annotation or ignore file. Any explanatory text should be behind a verbose flag. Senior engineers will distrust a tool that produces noisy output and will disable it.

The platform engineering team audience does not care about individual violations — they care about trends. Is the overall API quality of the organization improving over time? Which teams consistently produce high-quality specs and which need support? What is the distribution of violation types across the API portfolio? They need aggregate dashboards, not per-violation reports.

Think through the architectural implications. A single validation engine could serve all three audiences if the output layer is designed carefully: the same underlying analysis with different presentation modes. But the audiences also have different update frequency needs: platform dashboards need historical data retention, senior engineers need real-time CLI feedback, junior developers need IDE integration.

What is the right model for rule severity in this multi-audience context? A rule that is a hard error for senior engineers might be a gentle suggestion for junior developers. Should severity be audience-configurable, or should rules have fixed severities with audience-specific display filtering? How does this affect the usefulness of the tool as an organizational quality gate?
